Access Bank Plc has reported a Profit After Tax (PAT) of N97.5 billion for the group in 2019 financial, representing a 2.7% increase over the N94.98 billion posted in the preceding year. The lenders audited financial statement for the year under review sent to the Nigerian Stock Exchange, shows improvement in most of its performance indicators. The gross earnings stood at N666.75 billion as against the N528.74 billion recorded for the corresponding period for 2018. This shows a 26.10% increase. The net interest income for full-year 2019 was N277.2 billion representing 59.7% increase over the income in 2018, while bank’s net fee and commission income for full-year 2019 stood at N74.05 billion as against the N52.5 billion recorded in 2018. The profit before tax for the group for full-year 2019 stood at N115.38 billion as against the N103.2 billion that was recorded for the corresponding period in 2018. This represents an 11.8% increase. The bank’s balance sheet indicates increase in loans and advances to customers. Specifically, the lender’s loans and advances to customers during the year under review stood at N2.9 trillion as against the N1.9 trillion recorded in 2018, representing a 46.04% increase. Deposits by customers rose to N4.25 trillion in 2019 as against the N2.56 trillion recorded in 2018. This represents a 65.9% increase. Commenting on the performance, the bank’s Group Managing Director, Mr. Herbert Wigwe, said “Following the successful completion of the merger with Diamond Bank in March 2019, we have now fully positioned ourselves in the retail market with a view to bringing the power of banking to the doorsteps of millions. “We are providing a broader platform to facilitate payments services in Nigeria and across Africa, by harnessing our significantly enhanced digital technology capabilities,” Wigwe said. He said that the bank had made solid progress in line with its 2018-2022 five-year strategy and remained committed to the achievement of its strategic imperatives going forward. According to him, the bank will continue to invest in its people, technology and most importantly, its product offerings to customers. “Our focus is to become the world’s most respected African bank by leveraging on the strength of our retail and wholesale business to provide unrivalled value to our customers,” the banker added. LAGOS: Access Bank records N95bn profit in 2018 Skye Bank earnings rise 33 per cent in 2015 half year Access Bank declares N95bn profit for 2018